{"id":"2302.09056","submitter":"Siro Moreno Mart\\'in","authors":"Siro Moreno-Mart\\'in, Llu\\'is Ros, and Enric Celaya","title":"Collocation methods for second and higher order systems","comments":"21 pages, 7 figures, 5 tables. Submitted to Autonomous Robots RSS\n  2022 special issue","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is often unnoticed that the predominant way to use collocation methods is\nfundamentally flawed when applied to optimal control in robotics. Such methods\nassume that the system dynamics is given by a first order ODE, whereas robots\nare often governed by a second or higher order ODE involving configuration\nvariables and their time derivatives. To apply a collocation method, therefore,\nthe usual practice is to resort to the well known procedure of casting an M th\norder ODE into M first order ones. This manipulation, which in the continuous\ndomain is perfectly valid, leads to inconsistencies when the problem is\ndiscretized. Since the configuration variables and their time derivatives are\napproximated with polynomials of the same degree, their differential\ndependencies cannot be fulfilled, and the actual dynamics is not satisfied, not\neven at the collocation points. This paper draws attention to this problem, and\ndevelops improved versions of the trapezoidal and Hermite-Simpson collocation\nmethods that do not present these inconsistencies. In many cases, the new\nmethods reduce the dynamic transcription error in one order of magnitude, or\neven more, without noticeably increasing the cost of computing the solutions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Feb 2023 18:44:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-20"}
